                            <comment id="15301" author="sethladd" created="Sun, 6 Nov 2005 18:30:03 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The simple patch adding final setCommandName() and final getCommandName().  Stolen from BaseCommandController.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15308" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Mon, 7 Nov 2005 07:58:43 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Actually, why would you want to specify a custom command name in the first place? It&apos;s only used for the binding process, effectively at best showing up in the BindException thrown. In contrast to form controllers, the command name will never be used as model attribute key... and each controller method might declare a different command class.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, I would argue that a &quot;protected String getCommandName(Object command)&quot; template method would be more appropriate: allowing for overriding the command name on a per-command basis. I&apos;ve just added this. What do you think?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;BTW, in general, I would recommend direct ServletRequestDataBinder usage in a MultiActionController method (or also in a plain Controller implementation) instead of relying on a declared command argument. Such library-style usage of a ServletRequestDataBinder allows for a great level of flexibility.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15309" author="sethladd" created="Mon, 7 Nov 2005 08:07:43 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi Juergen,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As long as there is still a way to override the command name, we should be good.  I can see the case where controller chaining or fine grained model manipulation might create a conflict with the name &quot;command&quot;.  A getCommandName() is much better solution, because as you mention each method might use a different command class.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thanks!&lt;br/&gt;
Seth&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15315" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Mon, 7 Nov 2005 19:02:33 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;OK, so I consider this issue resolved then &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/images/icons/emoticons/smile.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15330" author="sethladd" created="Tue, 8 Nov 2005 10:38:53 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Many thanks!&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
